ance-code/>.


From: Raffaella del Prete <raffaellanz@icloud.com>
Sent: Monday, July 14, 2025 5:50 PM
To: Grant Metson <Grant.Metson@tower.co.nz>
Cc: Chris Cornwall <Chris.Cornwall@tower.co.nz>; Claims <Claims@tower.co.nz>
Subject: Re: Asbestos Report - Negative. 23 Mays Road, Devonport. C90306048

Hi Grant, Great to hear the asbestos report came back clear=E2=80=94fantast=
ic news! I'm happy for Asset Restore to begin the initial fire and smoke cl=
ean. I=E2=80=99m available to meet them at the property tomorrow (Tuesday) =
before 8 am (you can reach me at


Hi Grant,

Great to hear the asbestos report came back clear=E2=80=94fantastic news! I=
'm happy for Asset Restore to begin the initial fire and smoke clean. I=E2=
=80=99m available to meet them at the property tomorrow (Tuesday) before 8=
=E2=80=AFam (you can reach me at 0275089102), or on Wednesday anytime befor=
e 11=E2=80=AFam.

Just a quick reminder regarding the contents insurance: As discussed with C=
hris, I=E2=80=99ve removed several items from the property following the fi=
re=E2=80=94particularly electronics and lithium-powered devices, which coul=
d present a safety risk. Could you please advise on the next steps for asse=
ssing these?

Lastly, regarding the Assessment-Only Focus, I=E2=80=99m unclear on what =
=E2=80=9CThis will occur as per process=E2=80=9D means. Could you clarify w=
hat the process entails?

Kind regards,
Raffaella




On 14 Jul 2025, at 3:21=E2=80=AFPM, Grant Metson <Grant.Metson@tower.co.nz<=
mailto:Grant.Metson@tower.co.nz>> wrote:

Hi Rafaella,
Please find attached for your records a copy of the Asbestos Survey which w=
e have just received.
There was no asbestos found to be present within the structure, the surroun=
ds, the contents or any of the debris.
We are now ready to move onto the next stage in the process which will be t=
o undertake and complete as follows:

Contents Appraisal
Contents Removal
Full decontamination clean upstairs level.
Strip-out dwelling to provide visibility for scope of works
All of the stages/processes listed above can be completed in chronological =
order as above, by Asset Restore.

Below I have provided answers in blue to your recent questions. Which I tru=
st will allow us to move forward with the claim progression.


  *   Clarify Claim Scope: Is this the plan for both house and contents cla=
ims? If so, should it therefore be linked to both policy numbers to ensure =
all coverage is included? The structural claim will require a scope -of wor=
ks which is identified in the process list. The contents claim will have a =
schedule of contents determined. This is also listed I the process list pro=
vided. The 2 do not need to be linked. They can be cross referenced if need=
ed.
  *   Prioritize Health & Safety: I=E2=80=99d feel more comfortable if we s=
cheduled independent assessments (electrical, structural, gas, moisture/mou=
ld) before any major work, alongside the July 9 asbestos survey. The master=
 electrician=E2=80=99s finding that the property is uninhabitable due to el=
ectrical hazards is a key concern. This can all be scheduled now that we ha=
ve asbestos clearance. Do you want me to schedule this to occur ASAP?
  *   Assessment-Only Focus: As previously expressed, could we limit initia=
l tasks to enabling damage assessment (e.g., securing the site, debris remo=
val) rather than repairs (e.g., upstairs decontamination, curtain cleaning)=
? This would allow for a thorough evaluation and mutual agreement on remedi=
ation. The planned upstairs cleaning (July 21-25) feels premature for these=
 reasons:

     *   We need to assess damage before repair to preserve evidence. This =
will occur as per process.
     *   If the gas unit (likely damaged) requires removal, the ceiling may=
 need cutting, necessitating re-cleaning. Yes =E2=80=93 but this will form =
part of the repair process. It all needs to be assessed first.
     *   The electrician=E2=80=99s uninhabitable ruling requires electrical=
 work first. This will occur as per process.
     *   Firefighters switched off water (possibly gas?) and electricity, w=
hich must be assessed and remediated. This will occur as per process.
     *   With 4 pets and hybrid work, noisy basement/deck/roof work makes l=
iving there untenable until completed. That is your decision when you choos=
e to re-occupy. There is no pressure from your insurer to do so.

  *   Asbestos Survey Details: While I=E2=80=99m supportive of the July 9 s=
urvey, could you please share who will conduct it, the scope and tests invo=
lved, and how I can independently verify the results? Also, can the funding=
 for this be covered under the claim preparation provision?Provided and sha=
red with you.
  *   Structural Engineer Guidelines: I previously asked about guidelines f=
or paying a structural engineer, as per the provision for claim preparation=
. Could you please provide these, as I believe an independent assessment sh=
ould precede any repair work? Agreed. It will precede repair work =E2=80=93=
 but the site must be cleaned and cleared first so the structure can be pro=
perly assessed.
One of the things I should underline is that with any claim of this nature =
there are multiple cleaning processes which occur =E2=80=93 these are norma=
lly as follows:


  1.  Initial fire/smoke clean: to allow for detailed and accurate structur=
al assessment. To reduce smoke and other claim related odors. To prevent fu=
rther contamination and spreading of soot, etc.
  2.  Subsequent and multiple site cleans during repair works: this is a co=
nstant process of keeping the site tidy.
  3.  Final professional clean: this is completed before the home is re-occ=
upied.

My apologies =E2=80=93 I was not clear enough to explain that the cleaning =
process is not singular and final =E2=80=93 it is part of an ongoing proces=
s as described above.

Please let me know when we can issue instructions for Asset Managers to con=
tinue with the next steps in the process provided.
Best Regards,
Grant.

